Red Wine Quality Exploration by Karina Lund

Dataset I analyzed contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables of the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (excellent).

Which chemical properties influence the quality of red wines? is the question I will try to find answer to.

Univariate plots

Acids

The principal organic acids found in grapes are tartaric and malic, to a small extent, citric and others. Tartaric acid (fixed acidity) and malic acid account for over 90% of the total acids present.

Fixed acidity in dataset has a range from 4.6 to 15.90 g/dm, while volatile and citric acids have a range from 0.12 to 1.5 and 0 to 1 respectively.

Volatile acidity is responsible for the sour taste of vinegar. An excessive amount of acetic acid is also considered a wine fault.

Citric acid increases acidity and gives a fresh flavor. There are over 150 wines that doesnt contain citric acid at all. That is a normal situation because many types of red wines do not contain any citric acid.

Sulfur dioxide

Sulfur dioxide serves as an antibiotic and antioxidant, protecting wine from spoilage by bacteria and oxidation. Its antimicrobial action also helps to minimize volatile acidity. The nose will be able to detect SO2 in wine in the range of 15-40 ppm or higher dosage. If wine contains too much sulphur, person can be able to taste it and thats nasty taste.

There is no wine in dataset that are totally free for sulfur dioxide. Naturally occurring sulfites are generated in very small amounts ranging from 6 to 40 ppm. Most of wines in collection have a free sulfur dioxide under 21 mg/dm and a total sulfur dioxide under 62 mg/dm. There are two wines that have a very high total sulfur dioxide compared to others.

Total SO2 = Free SO2 + Bound SO2.
If the wine is bottle-aged, the SO2 will decrease as more sulfites react with other chemical constituents (sugars, acetaldehyde or phenolic compounds) in the wine and become bound. Bound sulfur dioxide can be 50 - 90% of the amount of SO2 added to wine. I will create a new variable for bound SO2.

Sugar, chlorides, sulphates

Residual Sugar is the level of glucose and fructose (grape sugars) that are not converted into alcohol during fermentation.

Sodium chloride shows amount of salt in the wine.

Potassium sulphate is a wine stabilizer. It has a bitter, salty taste.

Residual Sugar, chlorides and sulphates are right skewed, thats why log10 transformation is used.

Alcohol, density and pH

Alcohol directly correlates to the ripeness (sugar content) of grapes. As grapes ferment, the sugar converts to alcohol.

Density in wine is generally used as a measure of the conversion of sugar to alcohol.

Winemakers use pH as a way to measure ripeness in relation to acidity. Low pH wines will taste tart and crisp, while higher pH wines are more susceptible to bacterial growth. Most wine pHs fall around 3 or 4. pH from 3.3 to 3.6 is best for red wines. Most wines in dataset has pH from 3.2 to 3.4.

Density and pH are distributed normally.

Quality

There is no wine, that have got worst or best scores. Most of tested wines have been rated by experts as average. I will create a new variable rating by cutting quality in groups of 2.

redwine$rating<- cut(redwine$quality, breaks = c(0,2,4,6,8,10))

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Dataset contains 1599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine, such as fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, sodium chloride, free and total sulfur dioxides, density, pH, sulphates and alcohol. Dataset also includes a quality rating of wine provided by experts. Dataset doesnt contain any missing values. All columns are numerical.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

I would like to determine which properties influence the quality of red wines most. The main feature of interest is quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I can assume that acidity, alcohol and sugar influence the quality of red wine. Volatile acidity is responsible for the sour taste of vinegar. Citric acid gives a fresh flavor. Sugar gives sweetness. It also could be sulfur dioxide, because high level of it can be detected by nose. Or sulphate, because of bitter, salty taste.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I created 2 new variables:
* bound SO2, which is difference between Total and Free SO2;
* rating: for break quality in groups of 2.

Fixed and volatile acidity plots are right skewed, with some outliers with high amount of acids. Citric acid histogram has 3 peaks: 0, 0.25 and 0.5 g/dm. Peak with 0 g/dm if citric acid is highest. That can be explain by a fact that some wines dont contain any citric acid at all.

Free and total sulfur dioxide plots are right skewed too. Free sulfur dioxide distribution has some outliers for values from 66-72. And Total sulfur dioxide have 2 outliers for value near 300 mg/dm.

Residual Sugar, chlorides and sulphates plots are right skewed and were log-transformed. Distribution of pH and density is normal. Since data is clean and does not contain any NA values, I have not done any operation on data.

Relationship between other variables

There are some rules regarding wine components, which I would like to check:

pH and acidity

lower the pH, the higher the total acidity in the wine"

There are more than just 3 acids in wine, but here I used acids I have in dataset. Scatterplot shows that some of acids and pH has a visible negative correlation. Pearson correlation coefficient is -0.68, which indicates a near strong relation.

##        cor 
## -0.6834838

But there is something interesting, fixed acidity and citric acid have negative correlation coefficients: -0.68 and -0.54, but volatile acidity has positive 0.23. Its a weak correlation, but it should be negative.

Alcohol and density

Alcohol level can be measured with wine hydrometer, which measure density. Since density of ethanol is 0.7893 g/cm, which is lower than water, more alcohol will cured to lower density. Thats why I expect negative relationship between these two variables.

Conclusion I make here is that higher alcohol concentration gives more dense.

Acids and density

Lets see relationship between acids and density. Density of acids, found in dataset are:
* Tartaric acid: 1.79 g/cm
* Acetic acid: 1.05 g/cm
* Citric acid: 1.66 g/cm

I expect that there will be a positive correlation between all 3 acids and density and that tartaric acid and citric acid will have higher correlations than acetic. Since density of citric acetic acid are almost equals 1 (density of the water).

This correlation is weaker than correlation between acids and pH, but scatterplot still shows negative trend.

There are other strong correlations from pair plots.

Sulfur dioxides

Total sulfur dioxide is a sum of free SO2 and bound SO2.

I want also to look at bound SO2 and see how it correlated to free SO2 and total SO2. If the wine is bottle-aged, the SO2 will decrease as more sulfites react with other chemical constituents (sugars, acetaldehyde or phenolic compounds) in the wine and become bound. Bound sulfur dioxide can be 50 - 90% of the amount of SO2 added to wine.

Since both free and bound SO2 are parts of Total SO2, correlation between them and total SO2 are high.

There is a very strong correlation (0.96) between bound and total sulfur dioxides. I think that it is why scatterplots for free SO2 vs total SO2 and free SO2 vs bound SO2 looks very similar.

Correlation between free and bound sulfur dioxide is not so high as expected. Of course, there are a lot of factors affect to what amount of free SO2 will bind.

I wish I had more properties, for example age, so I could analyze how amount of free and bound SO2 depends on wine age.

pH and density

This scatterplot looks very interesting. pH and density of wines from dataset are very concentrated in one sector: where pH is from 3.2 to 3.4 and density is between 0.994 and 0.9975.

Correlation between pH and density are negative and equals -0.34.

Acids

Fixed acidity and citric acid have strong positive correlation. Its expected since citric acid is a component of tartaric acid. Fixed and volatile acidities, citric acid and volatile acidity have a negative correlation. First pair of acids has a weaker connection than other.

Reflection

I dont drink alcohol, so I though this analysis can help me to get learn something about wines and expand my knowledge area.
I was excited to start analysis and find about which one (or may be more) attributes affects wine quality.

Dataset I analyzed contains 1599 wine samples with 12 attributes. One of them is quality, graded by experts. I started with univariate analysis (analysis of each attribute) using histogram plots, looking to distributions. I met a little difficulty because I knew nothing about wines, so I spend a lot of time on this stage, reading articles about wines characteristics and finding information about each attributes, like what values are normal and how high values of attributes affects taste of wine.

After that I started a bivariate analysis. Pairs plot helped me to see all correlations between variables. I used it as basis for the rest of analysis. I used box plots and scatterplots to see how 2 variables are related to each other. Of course I was focused more on relations with wine quality. But when I analyzed other variables I felt that Im missing some chemistry knowledge to understand why variables are correlated. This stage helped me to get closer to the answer of main question.

Next step was multivariate analysis, it clarified my findings by use of colored scatterplots. On this stage I also calculated a linear model for 4 most correlated to quality attributes.

After analyzing red wine dataset, I came up with following results:
* None of wines have very poor (1,2) or excellent (9,10) quality. 83% of wines have quality of 5 and 6. This can make it harder to determine what makes good wine vs.bad wine.
* 4 most correlated to quality attributes are: alcohol, volatile acidity, sulphates and citric acid.
Strongest correlation is with alcohol and equals 0.48. * Red wines with higher quality have mostly higher alcohol level, less volatile acidity, more sulphates and more citric acid
* Fixed acidity has several strong correlations in dataset. It positively correlated to citric acids and density (coef 0.67) and negatively with pH (-0.68)
* Bound sulfur dioxide has correlation coefficient equals to 0.95 with total sulfur dioxide. Total SO2 = Free SO2 + Bound SO2. Wines with qualities of 2,3,7 and 8 have very low bound SO2 amount.
* Created linear model covered just 33,6% of the variability in quality, which I think is very low. I wouldnt use this model to predict wine quality.

Highest correlation with quality Ive got was 0.48 and I am not satisfied with a linear model Ive got. There was one more difficulty I met between this stage and nest stage is trying to understand what wine quality means. What criteria experts have used during wine grading? Was is just taste score or not? Also, I really wish I could have more attributes to analyze, like wine age, price, region, grape type. All these could help to build more precise linear model, which I could use to determine what bottle of red wine, Ive got some present, I should keep to myself and what I can give away;)
